The paper proposes a deep learning approach using generative adversarial networks (GANs) to correct differences in multi-site neuroimaging data. This involves transforming T1-weighted brain images collected from two different sites into MR images from the same site. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as it deals with image processing and analysis. Additionally, the use of GANs suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also involves training the model to estimate two distributions and transform examples from one distribution into the other, which suggests that it may belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with medical imaging, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
